{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2d449514-baa6-4aa8-9d59-7f6c2d82066a","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n  (Or point to a built DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourServer.dll`)\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector launches your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Use the UI tabs** to:\n- **Tools** → list and invoke your tools with test inputs\n- **Resources / Prompts** → test other MCP capabilities\n- View raw JSON-RPC messages in the log pane for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout only**. Use **stderr** for any logging/diagnostics, otherwise the Inspector can't parse the stream.\n- If using `launchSettings.json` or environment variables, you can set them in the Inspector's \"Environment Variables\" section before connecting.\n- Add `--no-build` to the arguments if you've already built, for faster startup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5e227a6a-e1e8-4918-95d1-ff7a28f2aab2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to search any codebase for this. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"158D:2D9367:308472E:3534706:69FBE5CA"},"id":"91d76e88-fd8b-4242-8775-cb358cf4c832","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:07:34.029Z","parentId":"ef7c4780-4e37-4429-9836-ad024bfa2afc"}
